### What to Do

Create a benchmark suite to measure and track hook mode performance. The hook MUST complete in <50ms to avoid slowing down agents.

### Why Performance Matters

AI agents invoke dcg on EVERY command. If dcg adds 100ms+ latency, the agent feels sluggish. Target: <50ms p99 latency.

### Benchmark Suite

```rust
// benches/hook_latency.rs
use criterion::{black_box, criterion_group, criterion_main, Criterion, BenchmarkId};
use dcg::{Config, evaluate_command};

fn bench_evaluate_command(c: &mut Criterion) {
    let config = Config::default_with_packs();

    let commands = vec![
        ("safe_echo", "echo hello"),
        ("safe_ls", "ls -la"),
        ("denied_rm", "rm -rf /"),
        ("denied_git_force", "git push --force origin main"),
        ("long_command", &"echo ".repeat(100)),
    ];

    let mut group = c.benchmark_group("evaluate_command");
    group.measurement_time(std::time::Duration::from_secs(10));

    for (name, cmd) in commands {
        group.bench_with_input(
            BenchmarkId::new("latency", name),
            &cmd,
            |b, cmd| {
                b.iter(|| {
                    evaluate_command(black_box(cmd), &config)
                })
            },
        );
    }

    group.finish();
}

fn bench_full_hook_mode(c: &mut Criterion) {
    // Benchmark full hook mode including I/O
    c.bench_function("hook_mode_full", |b| {
        b.iter(|| {
            let output = std::process::Command::new("./target/release/dcg")
                .arg("--hook-mode")
                .stdin(std::process::Stdio::piped())
                .stdout(std::process::Stdio::piped())
                .stderr(std::process::Stdio::null())
                .spawn()
                .unwrap();

            // Write command
            output.stdin.as_ref().unwrap()
                .write_all(b"echo hello\n")
                .unwrap();

            // Read response
            let result = output.wait_with_output().unwrap();
            black_box(result.stdout)
        })
    });
}

criterion_group!(benches, bench_evaluate_command, bench_full_hook_mode);
criterion_main!(benches);
```

### Performance Targets

| Metric | Target | Hard Limit |
|--------|--------|------------|
| evaluate_command p50 | <10ms | 25ms |
| evaluate_command p99 | <25ms | 50ms |
| full_hook_mode p50 | <25ms | 50ms |
| full_hook_mode p99 | <50ms | 100ms |

### CI Integration

```yaml
# .github/workflows/bench.yml
- name: Run benchmarks
  run: cargo bench --features rich-output -- --save-baseline main

- name: Compare against baseline
  run: cargo bench --features rich-output -- --baseline main --compare
```

### Performance Regression Detection

Create a script that fails CI if performance regresses:

```bash
# scripts/check_perf.sh
RESULT=$(cargo bench --features rich-output -- --baseline main 2>&1)
if echo "$RESULT" | grep -q "Performance has regressed"; then
    echo "FAIL: Performance regression detected"
    echo "$RESULT"
    exit 1
fi
```

### Memory Profiling

Also track memory usage:

```rust
#[test]
fn memory_usage_acceptable() {
    let before = get_memory_usage();
    for _ in 0..1000 {
        evaluate_command("rm -rf /", &config);
    }
    let after = get_memory_usage();

    // Should not leak memory
    assert!(after - before < 10_000_000); // 10MB max growth
}
```
